<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900625-0162</DOCNO><DOCID>900625-0162.</DOCID><HL>   Who's News:   Manager Revamp   Continues at Bank   Of New England   ----   By Gary Putka   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>06/25/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   NEB WNEWS</CO><IN>BANKS (BNK)</IN><LP>   BOSTON -- Bank of New England Corp. moved Leo R. Breitmanto a new vice chairman's post and hired D. Bruce Wheeler tosucceed him as president of its main bank unit.   The changes were the latest in a nearly continuousmanagement reshuffling this year, since the bank begandealing with losses and a mountain of bad loans in theslumping Northeast economy. Mr. Wheeler's hiring as presidentof Bank of New England N.A. comes only five months after Mr.Breitman was moved into the post and bears the imprint ofLawrence K. Fish, the parent company's chairman and chiefexecutive officer since March.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Wheeler, currently executive vice president of FirstNationwide Bank, of California, said he plans to pursueopportunities in mortgage lending and in retail banking in aneffort to &quot;get on the offense a little bit&quot; in solving thebank's problems. Mr. Fish reversed a plan to sell home-equityloans after taking the reins and also said he wants toexploit the bank's extensive retail operations in hisrecovery plan.   In his new post, Mr. Breitman will also become seniorcredit policy officer. Mr. Wheeler, who managed Massachusettsbanking operations for Bank of Boston from 1982 until 1989,will be responsible for corporate and retail banking,commercial real estate and trust and private banking.   Mr. Wheeler said in an interview that recent thriftfailures and cutbacks in mortgage lending in New Englandpresented an opportunity for new lending to the bank. He saida large portion of any new loans generated would be sold intothe secondary market so they wouldn't put pressure onregulatory capital ratios.   Bank of New England reported a $1.11 billion loss in lastyear's fourth quarter, and a $46 million loss in its firstquarter. It lost about $7 billion in deposits during a runthat followed disclosure of its problems, and is cuttingabout a third of its staff, while total assets are down to$25 billion from a peak of about $30 billion. Further assetsales are planned.   Mr. Wheeler said only 2% of the bank's customers have beenlost, suggesting a possibility of rebuilding its commercialloan portfolio. &quot;There's still a lot of creditworthycustomers in New England,&quot; he said.</TEXT></DOC>